definition.value: Catalysis of the transfer of a solute or solutes from one side of a membrane to the other according to the reaction -  triose-phosphate(out) + phosphate(in) -eq- triose-phosphate(in) + phosphate(out).
Catalysis of the transfer of a solute or solutes from one side of a membrane to the other according to the reaction -  nitrate(out) + H+(out) -eq- nitrate(in) + H+(in).
Catalysis of the transfer of a solute or solutes from one side of a membrane to the other according to the reaction -  auxin(out) + H+(out) -eq- auxin(in) + H+(in).

Catalysis of the transfer of phosphate from one side of the membrane to the other. In low-affinity transport the transporter is able to bind the solute only if it is present at very high concentrations.
Catalysis of the transfer of a solute or solutes from one side of a membrane to the other according to the reaction -  K+(out) + Na+(out) -eq- K+(in) + Na+(in).

Catalysis of the transfer of a solute or solutes from one side of a membrane to the other according to the reaction -  sulfate(out) + H+(out) -eq- sulfate(in) + H+(in). In high-affinity transport the transporter is able to bind the solute even if it is only present at very low concentrations.

Catalysis of the transfer of a solute or solutes from one side of a membrane to the other according to the reaction -  sulfate(out) + H+(out) -eq- sulfate(in) + H+(in). In low-affinity transport the transporter is able to bind the solute only if it is present at very high concentrations.
Catalysis of the hydrolysis of pyrophosphate, which generates a proton motive force.
Catalysis of the transfer of a solute or solutes from one side of a membrane to the other according to the reaction -  hexose(out) + H+(out) -eq- hexose(in) + H+(in).
Catalysis of the reaction -  L-arabinose + ATP -eq- beta-L-arabinose 1-phosphate + ADP + 2 H(+).
Catalysis of the reaction -  nitrite + NAD+ + H2O -eq- nitrate + NADH + H+.

The lipid bilayer surrounding a vacuole that retains the same shape regardless of cell cycle phase. The membrane separates its contents from the cytoplasm of the cell. An example of this component is found in Arabidopsis thaliana.
The inner, i.e. lumen-facing, lipid bilayer of the chloroplast envelope -  also faces the chloroplast stroma.
The outer, i.e. cytoplasm-facing, lipid bilayer of the chloroplast envelope.

The antenna complex of photosystem I. A photosystem has two closely linked components, an antenna containing light-absorbing pigments and a reaction center. Each antenna contains one or more light-harvesting complexes (LHCs).

The antenna complex of photosystem II. A photosystem has two closely linked components, an antenna containing light-absorbing pigments and a reaction center. Each antenna contains one or more light-harvesting complexes (LHCs).

Combining with a signal and transmitting the signal from one side of the membrane to the other to initiate a change in cell activity by catalysis of the reaction -  ATP + a protein-L-histidine -eq- ADP + a protein-L-histidine phosphate.
Catalysis of the reaction -  1-aminocyclopropane-1-carboxylate + L-ascorbate + O(2) -eq- CO(2) + dehydroascorbate + ethylene + 2 H(2)O + hydrogen cyanide. Ethene is also known as ethylene.
Catalysis of the reaction -  AMP + dimethylallyl diphosphate -eq- N(6)-(dimethylallyl)adenosine 5'-phosphate + diphosphate.
A Clp endopeptidase complex located in the chloroplast.
A Clp endopeptidase complex located in the mitochondrion.

A plastid that contains unstacked, phycobilisome-bearing thylakoid membranes and is surrounded by a double membrane with a peptidoglycan layer in the intermembrane space between the two envelope membranes. Cyanelles are characteristic of algae in the class Glaucophyta, and may represent an ancestral form of plastid.
A thylakoid found in a cyanelle, which is a type of plastid found in certain algae. The cyanelle contains a photosynthetic membrane resembling that of cyanobacteria.
The function of absorbing and responding to incidental electromagnetic radiation, particularly visible light. The response may involve a change in conformation.
The function of absorbing and responding to electromagnetic radiation with a wavelength of approximately 400-470nm. The response may involve a change in conformation.

label.value: red or far-red light photoreceptor activity

definition.value: The function of absorbing and responding to electromagnetic radiation with a wavelength of approximately 660-730nm. The response may involve a change in conformation.
Combining with a cytokinin and transmitting the signal from one side of the membrane to the other to initiate a change in cell activity.

label.value: transmembrane histidine kinase cytokinin receptor activity

definition.value: Combining with a cytokinin and transmitting the signal from one side of the membrane to the other to initiate a change in cell activity by catalysis of the reaction -  ATP + a protein-L-histidine -eq- ADP + a protein-L-histidine phosphate.
The leaflet of the plasma membrane that faces away from the cytoplasm and any proteins embedded or anchored in it or attached to its surface.
The leaflet the plasma membrane that faces the cytoplasm and any proteins embedded or anchored in it or attached to its surface.
Catalysis of the reaction -  ent-copalyl diphosphate -eq- ent-kaur-16-ene + diphosphate.
Catalysis of the reaction -  all-trans-geranylgeranyl diphosphate -eq- ent-copalyl diphosphate.
Catalysis of the oxidation of ubiquinol by diverting electrons from the standard electron transfer chain, transferring them from ubiquinol to oxygen and generating water as the product.
Catalysis of the removal of a C-5 double bond in the B ring of a sterol.
Catalysis of the reaction -  5-dehydroepisterol -eq- 24-methylenecholesterol.
The protein complex associated with the plasma membrane of certain plant cells (e.g. root cortex, epidermal cells) that functions to transport auxin out of the cell.
Catalysis of the reaction -  fatty acid (C-16 or longer) + 2-C -eq- fatty acid (C-16 or longer + 2-C).
A tetrameric complex of four different subunits which catalyzes the elongation of fatty acids chains 2 carbon units at a time in the synthesis of very long chain fatty acids.
Catalysis of the reaction -  octadecanal -eq- heptadecane + CO.

The region of the plasma membrane located at the basal end of the cell. Often used in reference to animal polarized epithelial membranes, where the basal membrane is the part attached to the extracellular matrix, or in plant cells, where the basal membrane is defined with respect to the zygotic axis.
Serves as a phospho-His intermediate enabling the transfer of phospho group between a hybrid kinase and a response regulator.
The side of the cell parallel to the zygotic axis.

Catalysis of the reactions -  ATP + a protein serine -eq- ADP + protein serine phosphate -  and ATP + a protein threonine -eq- ADP + protein threonine phosphate. These reactions are dependent on the presence of calcium ions.

Interacting selectively and non-covalently with an amino terminal propeptide, which functions as a sorting signal to sort away the soluble vacuolar protein from Golgi to lytic vacuole via clathrin-coated vesicles.
The double lipid bilayer enclosing the chloroplast and separating its contents from the rest of the cytoplasm -  includes the intermembrane space.
Catalysis of the reaction -  AMP + sulfite + acceptor -eq- adenylyl sulfate + reduced acceptor.
Catalysis of the reaction -  zeinoxanthin + NADPH + O2 + H+ -eq- lutein + NADP+ + H2O. Adds a hydroxyl group to the epsilon ring of the alpha-carotene.
Catalysis of a ring closure reaction.

Catalysis of the reaction -  alkene group + alcohol group on same molecule -eq- cyclic ether. Substrates are 2-methyl-6-phytyl-1,4- hydroquinone (forms delta-tocopherol) and 2,3-dimethyl-5-phytyl-1,4-hydroquinone (forms gamma-tocopherol).

label.value: proton motive force dependent protein transmembrane transporter activity

definition.value: Catalysis of the transfer of proteins from one side of the membrane to the other. Transportation is dependent on pH gradient across the membrane.
